messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full path:
- /cms/admin/user/{uid}

All methods acceptable (overrides others):
- False

HEAD:
- False

POST:
- False

OPTIONS:
- False

TRACE:
- False

GET:
- False

PUT:
- True

DELETE:
- False

PATCH:
- False

Explanation:
- The update_user handler is defined in app/api/cms/admin.py with the route decorator @admin_api.route("/user/<int:uid>", methods=["PUT"]). That registers only the PUT method on the admin_api blueprint for the path "/user/<int:uid]".
- The admin_api blueprint is registered in app/api/cms/__init__.py with url_prefix="/admin". That cms blueprint (returned by create_cms) is in turn registered in app/__init__.py with url_prefix="/cms". Combining prefixes yields the full path /cms + /admin + /user/{uid} â†’ /cms/admin/user/{uid}.
- Because the route decorator explicitly specifies methods=["PUT"], only PUT is accepted by this registered route. There is no code in this file that registers update_user for other HTTP methods, nor any code indicating acceptance of all methods; therefore "all methods" is False.
- The decision about HEAD/OPTIONS/etc. is made strictly from the code (route decorator). No code in the repository provided explicitly registers HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, GET, DELETE, PATCH, or POST for this particular update_user handler, so those are False. (Note: there is a separate delete_user handler that registers DELETE on the same path, but that is a different function; this answer pertains only to the update_user endpoint.)
